title: Alb(i)um Intimilium/Albintimilium
description: Alb(i)um Intimilium/Albintimilium (modern Ventimiglia) was the main settlement of the Ligurian tribe of the Intemelii. In the 2nd century BC it came under control of the Roman Republic. Albintimilium became a municipium in 89 BC in the tribus Falerna. In the same period the city walls were built with several towers. The city flourished in the early Imperial period with baths an acqueduct and a theater. In the 6th and early 7th century it was a Byzantine kastron coming under control of the Longobards in 641. During the 7th and 8th century the Roman city was slowly abandoned in favour of a smaller hilltop settlement focused around the Cathedral.

title: Album Ingaunum/Albingaunum

It was an important city and played a role in the civil wars during the last decades of the Roman Republic.

title: Herdoniae/Ardaneae/Civitas Serdonis
description: Herdonia was an ancient city of Apulia located along the via Minucia. The city was the site of two major engagements of the Second Punic War (212 and 210 B.C. respectively) both of which were Carthaginian victories. The city's extensive remains have been investigated by the Belgian Institute since the Second World War.

title: Hydruntum/Hydrous
description: A Greek city at the easternmost point of the Italian peninsula that sided against Rome in both the Pyrrhic and Hannibalic wars. In the time of the Roman Empire the city was located in the province of Calabria and was an embarkation point for ships leaving for Apollonia across the Adriatic Sea.

title: Kaneš
description: Kaneš or Kanesh (Hittite: Neša) is located adjacent to modern Kültepe thus at times the site is referred to as Kültepe Kaneš. The site was one of continuous occupation from the Chalcolithic period to the time of the Roman empire although its cultural zenith was as a major Hittite site that was the site of a large merchant quarter (kârum) of the Old Assyrian kingdom (ca. twentieth to sixteenth centuries BC).

title: Baeça

title: Acquarossa
description: Acquarossa was an Etruscan settlement that was abandoned in the sixth century BC. The settlement occupied a steep-sided plateau and had an area of approximately 32 ha.

title: Aequiculi
description: Aequiculi was a municipium in the territory of the Aequi.

title: Aesis
description: An Umbrian town that became a colonia civium Romanorum under the name of Aesis in 247 BC.

title: Alba Fucens
description: A town of the Aequi along the Marsic frontier where the Romans established a Latin colony in 304/3 B.C. Alba Fucens was a significant center of the middle republican period and became a place where Rome kept state prisoners including Syphax of Numidia Perseus of Macedonia and Bituitus king of the Arverni.

title: Allumiere

title: Amiternum
description: Amiternum was an ancient settlement of the Sabines that Rome captured in 293 BC. The settlement was situated at the intersection of four Roman roads: the Via Caecilia the Via Claudia Nova and the two branches of the Via Salaria. The historian Sallust was born at Amiternum in 86 BC.

title: Anguillara
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Anguillara

title: Arna

title: Arretium
description: Arretium (the Etruscan Aritim) was one of the duodecim populi Etruriae and described by Livy as one of the Capitae Etruriae.  The Romans captured the city in 311 B.C. and it became a station on the via Cassia.

title: Asciano
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Asciano

title: Asisium
description: A Roman settlement built over an Umbrian one on a western foothill of the Appenines. It received municipal status and was assigned to the  Tribus Sergia. Totila destroyed most of the city in A.D. 545.

title: Aternum
description: Aternum (modern Pescara) was a settlement at the mouth of the Aternus river.

title: Attidium
description: An ancient settlement of Umbria mentioned only by Pliny the Elder. Numerous inscriptions discovered at the site indicate that Attidium achieved the status of a municipium.

title: *Aufenginum
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 F4 *Aufenginum

title: Aufinum
description: Aufinum (modern Ofena) was an ancient center of the Abruzzo. Pliny lists the Aufinates Cismontani among the communities of the Vestini.

title: Auximum
description: Auximum (modern Osimo) is an ancient settlement of Picenum. The original foundation was likely carried out by Greeks from Ancona. The Romans made it a base for military operations from 174 B.C.

title: Aveia
description: Aveia was a settlement of the Vestini in the valley of the Aterno river.

title: Axia

title: Cetamura
description: Cetamura is an ancient hilltop settlement with occupation phases stretching from the Etruscans to the Romans to the Medieval period. The site is located near Gaiole Radda and Castellina in Chianti Italy.

description: Clusium the Etruscan Clevsin (modern Chiusi) was a major city of Etruria. Lars Porsena was a sixth century B.C. king of Clusium.

title: Corfinium
description: Corfinium was the principal city of the Paeligni in the valley of the Aternus river. The site becomes the capital of the breakaway Italic groups that oppose Rome during the Social War.

title: Cortona
description: An Umbrian city that under Etruscan influence expanded and came to be called 'Curtun'. Later it became the Roman colony of Cortino.

title: Cupra Maritima
description: Cupra Maritima was a coastal city of Picenum (regio V) assigned to the tribus Velina.

title: Cupra Montana
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Cupra Montana

title: Cures
description: Cures (also Cures Sabini) was a Sabine city located in the Tiber river valley along the Via Salaria. The Romans conquered Cures in 290 BC under M'. Curius Dentatus and granted it status as a municipium in the tribus Sergia.

title: Doganella
description: Doganella was an important Etruscan settlement of the Albegna valley occupied between ca. 600 and 400 B.C. The city may have comprised as many as 240 ha.

title: Eretum
description: Eretum was a settlement of the Sabines and is involved in legendary accounts of early Rome.

title: Faesulae
description: Faesulae (modern Fiesole) was an Etruscan foundation called Viesul Viśl or Vipsul. The city was conquered by Romans in 283 B.C. Sulla would settle Roman veterans there. Citizens of the town supported the conspiracy of Catiline.

title: Falerii Veteres
description: A Faliscan settlement (cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Falerii Veteres)

title: Falerio
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Falerio

title: Fanum Fortunae
description: Fanum Fortunae the site of a shrine to Fortuna is first mentioned in the ancient sources in 49 B.C. when Iulius Caesar held the town. An Augustan colony was established at the site and the Romans prevailed in the Battle of Fano in A.D. 271. The town was eventually destroyed by the Ostrogoths.

title: Ferentium
description: Ferentium (modern Ferento) was a city of Etruria first mentioned in the Liber Coloniarum ca. 123 BC that became a Roman municipium after the Social War. Substantial remains of the city remain; the site was the birthplace of Otho and noted for its fine stone monuments and statues.

title: Fescennium
description: Fescennium (modern Narce) was a Faliscan settlement located ca. 5 km south of Falerii Veteres.

title: *Firmidianum
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 D1 *Firmidianum

title: Firmum Picenum
description: Firmum Picenum was founded as a Latin colony in 264 BC with 6000 colonists. It received municipal status after 48 BC.

title: Florentia
description: Florentia (modern Florence / Firenze) was founded as a colony for military veterans ca. 80 B.C. by Lucius Cornelius Sulla.

title: Fontecchio
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 F4 Fontecchio

title: Foruli
description: Foruli was a Sabine town located between Amiternum and Interocrea.

title: Forum Aurelii
description: A settlement in Etruria situated on the Via Aurelia placed by between Centumcellae and Cosa by the Antonine Itinerary.

title: Forum Cassii
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Forum Cassii

title: Forum Clodii
description: An ancient road station on the Via Clodia.

title: Forum Decii
description: A town of the Sabines mentioned by Pliny the Elder.

title: Forum Flaminii

title: Forum Novum

title: Graviscae

title: Grotte di Castro
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Grotte di Castro

title: Hatria
description: An ancient city of Picenum that may have originated as colony established by Etruscans from Adria in the Veneto region.

title: Heba
description: A Roman colony that was established in the third or second century B.C. Heba lay near modern Magliano. Funerary evidence indicate previous Etruscan occupation at the site.

title: Helvia Ricina
description: An ancient settlement in Picenum at modern Villa Potenza in Marche Comune di Macerata Italy.

title: Helvillum
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 D2 Helvillum

title: Histonium
description: Histonium on the Adriatic coast was a chief town of the Frentani.

title: Horta
description: The Etruscan settlement of *Hurta (the modern Orte) was close to the Vadimonis Lacus where the Romans fought and won two engagements against Etruscan armies.

title: Interamna Nahars
description: An Umbrian center founded in the seventh century B.C. that became an important Roman municipality along the Via Flaminia.

title: Interamnia Praetuttiorum
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 F3 Interamnia Praetuttiorum

title: Interocrium
description: A Sabine town that was later known as a mansio on the course of the Via Salaria.

title: Interpromium
description: A village of the Marrucini forming a station on the Via Claudia Valeria between Corfinium and Teate.

title: Lucus Feroniae
description: A sanctuary and grove of Feronia and an associated settlement located along the Via Tiberina in the territory of Capena.

title: Luni sul Mignone
description: Luni sul Mignone is a site with archaeological evidence for habitation in the final second millennium BC continuing into the Italian Iron Age.

title: Mevaniola
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 B1 Mevaniola

title: Mola di Monte Gelato
description: An ancient settlement 30 km north of Rome that was excavated from 1986-90. An imperial villa existed on the site up until the third century AD.

title: Montedoro di Scapezzano

title: Musarna
description: Musarna is an ancient Etruscan settlement discovered in 1849 just west of Viterbo Italy. The École française de Rome has been conducting excavations at the site since 1983.

title: Nepet
description: Nepet had become a Roman town before 396 BC when Livy dubs it along with Sutrium as one of the keys to Etruria. It became a Roman colony in 383 BC and a municipium after the Social War.

title: Nequinum/Narnia
description: Nequinum/Narnia (modern Narni) was an ancient settlement in Umbria. It became a Latin colony in 299 BC.

title: Novilara
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Novilara

title: Nuceria
description: Nuceria (modern Nocera Umbra) is an ancient town in Umbria perhaps founded in the seventh century B.C. by Camerinum.

title: Numana
description: Numana was a settlement of ancient Picenum located south of Ancona.

title: Nursia
description: Nursia was the northernmost city of the Sabines.

title: Ocriculum
description: An ancient Umbrian city that became allied with Rome in 308 B.C.

title: [Orcla]
description: [Orcla] or Norchia is an ancient Etruscan settlement located near Tarquinia and along the line of the Roman Via Clodia.

title: Ortona
description: An ancient site in Italy that most likely originates with the Frentani.

title: Ostia Aterni
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 G4 Ostia Aterni

title: Ostra
description: Ostra was an ancient town of Umbria.

title: Paganica
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 E4 Paganica

title: Passo Corese

title: Pausulae
description: Pausulae was a town of Picenum mentioned by Pliny the Elder. It was a Municipium of Regio V.

title: Peltuinum
description: Peltuinum was a settlement of the Vestini located along the Via Claudia Nova. The town is notable as the birthplace of the Roman general  Gnaeus Domitius Corbulo.

title: Perusia
description: A city of ancient Umbrian and Etruscan origin Perusia aided Rome during the Second Punic War but was sieged and reduced by Octavian in the first century B.C. during campaigns against Lucius Antonius. It was rebuilt by Augustus and became Colonia Vibia Augusta Perusia quite late in A.D. 251-3 under Trebonianus Gallus.

title: Phalacrinae
description: A Roman town in which the emperor Vespasian was born in A.D. 9.

title: Piano Tondo
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 B2 Piano Tondo

title: Pinna

title: Pisaurum

title: Pitigliano

title: Pitino

title: Sarteano
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Sarteano

title: Sena Gallica
description: Located at the mouth of the river Misa Sena Gallica was founded by the Senonian Gauls in the fourth century BC and became the site of Rome's earliest Adriatic colony before 280 BC. Pompeius Magnus destroyed the city in 82 B.C.

title: Sentinum
description: An ancient town in the region of Italy now known as Le Marche Sentinum is perhaps best known for the pivotal Battle of Sentinum of the Third Samnite War that took place nearby in 295 BC.

title: Septempeda
description: Septempeda was an ancient settlement of Picenum. Its Roman phase began as a conciliabulum in the third century B.C.

title: Sestinum
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 C1 Sestinum

title: Sorano
description: Sorano was a Villanovan and later Etruscan settlement.

title: Sorrina
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Sorrina

title: Statonia
description: An ancient city of south Etruria.

title: Suasa
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 D1 Suasa

title: Superaequum
description: One of three towns of the Paeligni which possessed municipal rights.

title: Sutrium
description: An ancient settlement along the line of what would become the Roman Via Cassia and described by Livy together with Nepet as one of the keys to Etruria. A Latin colony was founded at the site after the fall of Veii.

title: Tadinae
description: Tadinae (Sant'Antonio della Rasina to the west of Gualdo Tadino) is an ancient municipium of Umbria and was a road station on the Via Flaminia.

title: Teate
description: Originally named Teate Marrucinorum Teate (modern Chieti) was the principal settlement of the Marrucini. Strabo attributes its origins to Arcadian Greeks.

title: Tifernum Mataurense
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 C1 Tifernum Mataurense

title: Tifernum Tiberinum
description: An Umbrian hilltown in the floodplain of the Tiber river north of Perusia.

title: Tiora Matiene
description: Tiora Matiene was the site of an ancient oracle of the god Mars.

title: Tolentinum
description: Tolentinum was a town of Picenum that is listed as having municipal status in the Liber Coloniarum.

title: Trea
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 E2 Trea

title: Trebiae
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Trebiae

title: Trebula Mutuesca
description: Trebula Mutuesca or Trebula Mutusca was one of two Sabina cities bearing the name Trebula.

title: Trevignano
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Trevignano

title: Tuder
description: Tuder modern Todi is an ancient city of Umbria. Its foundation likely occurred during the eighth/seventh centuries BC although legendary traditions associate the site with the activities of Herakles.

title: Tuficum
description: Tuficum was an ancient city of Umbria located on the Aesis river. It became a municipium of the tribus Oufentina.

title: Tuscana
description: An ancient city that traced its legendary origins to Ascanius son of Aeneas. The site became an important Etruscan mercantile center and eventually achieved Roman municipal status in 88 BC.

title: Urbs Salvia
description: An ancient city of Regio V (Picenum) where a Roman colony was founded in the second century B.C.

title: Urvinum Hortense
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Urvinum Hortense

title: Urvinum Mataurense
description: Urvinum Mataurense (modern Urbino).

title: Vacchereccia
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 D4 Vacchereccia

title: Velzna/*Volsinii Veteres/Urbiventus
description: Volsinii Veteres was one of the most powerful and important cities of Etruria as it was the location of the important federal sanctuary located at the Fanum Voltumnae.

title: Verucchio
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 C1 Verucchio

title: Vespasiae
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Vespasiae

title: Vettona
description: Vettona (modern Bettona) is an ancient settlement of Umbria located between Perusia and Mevania. Pliny the Elder lists it among the municipalities of Umbria and it also numbered as one of the “xv Populi Umbriae.

title: Vicus Martis
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 D3 Vicus Martis

title: Vicus Matrini
description: Vicus Matrini was a mansio along the Via Cassia located between Sutri and Forum Cassi. The site's name is attested on the Peutinger Table.

title: Vignanello
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 C4 Vignanello

title: Villalfonsina
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 H4 Villalfonsina

title: Visentium
description: Visentium (Bisenzio) was an Etruscan settlement located on the shore of Lago di Bolsena. The site has yielded especially important evidence for Iron Age and Etruscan period burials.

title: Volsinii
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 42 B3 Volsinii

title: Vulci
description: Vulci (originally Velch or Velx in Etruscan) was an Etruscan city 80 km northwest of Rome. Vulci was one of the duodecim populi Etruriae.

title: Acqua Acetosa
description: A settlement along the Via Laurentina that has yielded significant evidence for protohistoric occupation including funereal evidence of the eighth and seventh centuries BC

title: Acquafredda
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Acquafredda

title: Afilae
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 E2 Afilae

title: Alba Longa?
description: Alba Longa located in the Alban Hills southeast of Rome was the chief city and founder of the Latin League. Conflict with Rome caused Alba's destruction in the seventh century B.C. The legendary history of Romulus and Remus connects them to the royal lineage of the city.

title: Algidus
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Algidus

title: Alsium
description: Alsium served as a port for Caere together with Fregenae.

title: L’Altare
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 C3 L’Altare

title: Anagnia
description: Anagnia was a Hernican town that sided with Rome against the Volscians and later became civitas sine suffragio.

title: Annunziatella
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Annunziatella

title: Antemnae
description: Antemnae is an ancient Latin settlement located north of Rome near the point where the Anio and Tiber rivers intersect.  Connected with Rome's early history Antemnae was involved in episodes such as the 'Rape of the Sabine Women' and Romulus is said to have celebrated a triumph over the Antemnates in 752 BC.

title: Antium
description: Antium ranked as one of the most important and most powerful centers of Latium and was captured by Rome at the close of the Latin War in the fourth century B.C. Imperial Antium was well known for a number of coastal villas.

title: Aricia
description: Aricia is an ancient Latin settlement and a member of the Latin League.

title: Colle Monitola
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Colle Monitola

title: Colle Rotondo
description: Colle Rotondo was the site of a prehistoric settlement inhabited from the Bronze Age until the early Iron Age.

title: Cora
description: A Latin center in the Monti Lepini that was already a Roman municipium by 211 B.C.

title: Crustumerium
description: An ancient town of Latium located at the headwaters of the Allia river very close to the territory of the Sabines Crustumerium figures in Rome's early history. The Romans conquered the site in 500 BC and formed the tribus Crustumina or Clustumina  in 471 BC.

title: Ficana
description: An ancient city of Latium that was said to have been conquered by Ancus Marcius Ficana was located near the eleventh mile of the Via Ostiensis. Excavation at the site has produced important evidence for the urban center beginning from the eighth century BC. Pliny the Elder mentions Ficana as one of the lost cities of Latium.

title: Ficulea
description: Ficulea was an ancient city of Latium situated between Rome and Nomentum.

title: Fidenae
description: Fidenae was an ancient city of Latium.

title: Fregenae
description: An ancient town of Etruria Fregenae was located between Alsium and the mouth of the river Tiber.

title: Labicum
description: Originally a member of the Latin League the city of Labicum was taken by the Romans ca. 418 B.C. By the time of Augustus the site was almost certainly deserted and its precise location remains debated today.

title: Lanuvium
description: Lanuvium was an important city of Latium located south of the Alban Hills. After opposing Rome at the battle of Aricia (504 B.C.) and Lake Regillus (496 B.C.) Lanuvium was captured by the Romans in 338 B.C.

title: Monte dell'Oro
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 B2 Monte dell'Oro

title: Muraccio dell’Omo
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 C2 Muraccio dell’Omo

title: Nettuno
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 C4 Nettuno

title: Nomentum
description: The Latin town of Nomentum and Rome were linked by means of the Via Nomentana. In Livy's history the town a member of the Latin League is captured by Lucius Tarquinius Priscus. Nomentum was one of a number of towns captured by Tarquinius. The Romans granted the town civitas sine suffragio after 338 B.C.

title: Pedum?
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 D2 Pedum?

title: Pometia
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Pometia

title: Portus

title: La Rustica
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 C2 La Rustica

title: Sacer Mons
description: Sacer Mons is a hill on the banks of the Anio river and is connected traditionally with the episode of the secession of the Roman plebs of 494 BC.

title: S. Agata
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 B2 S. Agata

title: S. Rufina
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 B2 S. Rufina

title: Satricum
description: An ancient settlement on the right bank of the river Astura Satricum has a mixed heritage of Latins and Volscians. In 499 B.C. Satricum was a member of the Latin League but was under Volscian control in 488 B.C. The site is noted for its sanctuary of Mater Matuta.

title: Serrone di Bove
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 D3 Serrone di Bove

title: Setia
description: A Volscian settlement of the fifth century B.C. that became a Latin colony in 382 B.C.

title: Signia
description: A city of Latium Adjectum established as a Latin colony ca. 494 B.C.

title: La Storta
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 B1 La Storta

title: Sublaqueum
description: An ancient settlement located at modern Subiaco in Italy Sublaqueum was located in the territory of the Aequi that was annexed by Rome in 304 BC.

title: Tibur
description: A Sabine town 30 km east-north-east of Rome Tibur was the seat of the Tiburtine Sibyl.

title: Trebula Suffenas

title: Troia?
description: An ancient place cited: BAtlas 43 B3 Troia?

title: Tusculum
description: Tusculum was a Latin city of the Alban Hills in central Italy. After 381 BC Tusculum became the first municipium cum suffragio.

title: Valvisciolo
description: An Iron Age settlement and necropolis located in the Monti Lepini near the abbey of Valvisciolo characterized by polygonal masonry terrace walls. While the ancient name of the site is unknown various proposals have been raised including Sulmo (Savignoni Mengarelli) and Pometia (Ogilvie). The settlement corresponds to the Latial II B phase and occupation ends ca. the late sixth century BC.

title: Varia
description: Varia (modern Vicovaro) was a settlement of the Sabines.

title: Velitrae
description: Velitrae (modern Velletri) was an ancient Volscian settlement. In the Roman Republican period Velitrae was attacked by Marcus Furius Camillus (379 B.C.) and again by Cincinnatus (377 B.C.); the Romans controlled the site by 365 BC. The gens Octavia hailed from the city and a youthful Octavian spent time there.

title: Tchogha Zanbil
description: An ancient Elamite complex founded ca. 1250 BC by the king Untash-Napirisha.

title: Briteiros
description: The Citânia de Briteiros is an archaeological site of the Castro culture located in the northwestern part of the Iberian Peninsula.
